From: dfattal <dfattal@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 14 Jul 2026 01:10:04 -0700
Subject: [PATCH 27/41] =?UTF-8?q?displayxr:=20batched=20weave=20submit=20?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=E2=80=94=20one=20xrWeaveSubmitDXR=20per=20frame=20(spec=20v3)?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

The GPU-process sync weave did one synchronous xrWeaveSubmitDXR per visible
inline-3d element per frame (~1 ms fixed cost each on Viz's present thread),
capping a page at ~8-12 visible elements. This batches to ONE submit per
frame carrying N rects (runtime XR_DXR_weave SPEC_VERSION 3, chained
XrWeaveSubmitRectsDXR).

- third_party/displayxr XR_DXR_weave.h byte-synced from the runtime
  canonical v3 copy.
- DisplayXRWeaveClient: captures the runtime's reported extensionVersion
  (previously unread); new SubmitBatch packs the chained rect array and
  chunks past the 32-rect per-call cap. Spec-v2 runtimes report ok=false and
  callers keep the per-element Submit loop.
- DisplayXRWeaveGpu: BatchMode (sync + spec>=3) collapses the per-target
  keyed-mutex input pool into ONE window-sized legacy-DXGI shared input;
  WeaveCanvas/WeavePixels become copy-only (CopySubresourceRegion dest = the
  element's own window position, same copy count as before), and
  SubmitBatchSync does one snap + one submit + per-target result fan-out
  (fresh woven/fence handles ride the first entry; the rest carry 0 = reuse,
  which Phase B's shared-woven import already expects). The v2 per-target
  path is kept intact as the fallback.
- Viz WeaveCompositedSurface Phase A brackets the existing attempt_submit
  loop with BeginBatchSync/SubmitBatchSync in batch mode; Phase B unchanged
  (it was already shared-output-shaped).

Throttled VLOG(1) reports the one-submit batch cost (n, µs) for the
scaling measurement.
